# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emergency-light
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:emergency-light/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] An **apartment** (North American English), **flat** (British English, Indian English, South African English) or **unit** (Australian English), is a self-contained housing unit that occupies part of a building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The housing tenure of apartments also varies considerably, from large-scale public housing, to owner occupancy within what is legally a condominium (strata title or commonhold) or leasehold, to tenants renting from a private landlord.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The buildings that contain apartments may be called different things depending on size or country (see below).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The term *apartment* is favoured in North America (although in some Canadian cities, *flat* is used for a unit which is part of a house containing two or three units, typically one to a floor).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the UK and Australia, *flat* is the common term, although parts of the real estate industry has recently began using the term "apartment" for large upmarket flats, especially if their target group is foreign investors.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In some countries, the word "unit" is a more general term referring to both apartments and rental business suites.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The word 'unit' is generally used only in the context of a specific building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] "Mixed-use buildings" combine commercial and residential uses within the same structure.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Typically, mixed-use buildings consist of businesses on the lower floors (often retail in street-facing ground floor and supporting subterranean levels) and residential apartments on the upper floors.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Tenement law refers to the feudal basis of permanent property such as land or rents.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] It may be found combined as in "Messuage or Tenement" to encompass all the land, buildings and other assets of a property.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Most apartments are in buildings designed for the purpose, but large older houses are sometimes divided into apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The word *apartment* denotes a residential unit or section in a building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In some locations, particularly the United States, the word connotes a rental unit owned by the building owner, and is not typically used for a condominium.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In England and Wales, some flat owners own shares in the company that owns the freehold of the building as well as holding the flat under a lease.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This arrangement is commonly known as a "share of freehold" flat.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The freehold company has the right to collect annual ground rents from each of the flat owners in the building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The freeholder can also develop or sell the building, subject to the usual planning and restrictions that might apply.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This situation does not happen in Scotland, where long leasehold of residential property was previously unusual and now is impossible.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartment buildings are multi-story buildings where three or more residences are contained within one structure.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Such a building may be called an *apartment building*, *apartment complex*, *flat complex*, *block of flats*, *tenement* (Scotland),*tower block*, *high-rise* or, occasionally, *mansion block* (in British English), especially if it consists of many apartments for rent.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A high-rise apartment building is commonly referred to as a *residential tower*, *apartment tower*, or *block of flats* in Australia.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A high-rise building is defined by its height differently in various jurisdictions.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] It may be only residential, in which case it might also be called a tower block, or it might include other functions such as hotels, offices, or shops.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] There is no clear difference between a tower block and a skyscraper, although a building with fifty or more stories is generally considered a skyscraper.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] High-rise buildings became possible with the invention of the elevator (lift) and cheaper, more abundant building materials.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Their structural system usually is made of reinforced concrete and steel.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A low-rise building and mid-rise buildings have fewer stories, but the limits are not always clear.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Emporis defines a low-rise as "an enclosed structure below 35 metres [115 feet] which is divided into regular floor levels." The city of Toronto defines a mid-rise as a building between 4 and 12 stories.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Garden apartment buildings are usually one or two storey structures where the individual apartments open directly to the outdoors and where the building or complex offers landscaped grounds.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In American English, the distinction between rental apartments and condominiums is that while rental buildings are owned by a single entity and rented out to many, condominiums are owned individually, while their owners still pay a monthly or yearly fee for building upkeep.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Condominiums are often leased by their owner as rental apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A third alternative, the cooperative apartment building (or "co-op"), acts as a corporation with all of the tenants as shareholders of the building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Tenants in cooperative buildings do not own their apartment, but instead own a proportional number of shares of the entire cooperative.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] As in condominiums, cooperators pay a monthly fee for building upkeep.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Co-ops are common in cities such as New York, and have gained some popularity in other larger urban areas in the U.S.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In British English the usual word is "flat", but *apartment* is used by property developers to denote expensive "flats" in exclusive and expensive residential areas in, for example, parts of London such as Belgravia and Hampstead.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Scotland, it is called a block of flats or, if it is a traditional sandstone building, a *tenement*, a term which has a negative connotation elsewhere.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In India and South Africa, the words "flat" and "apartment" are interchangeably used to refer to a housing unit in a building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The word "flat" is also used to refer to multi-story dwellings that have lifts.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Australian English and New Zealand English traditionally used the term *flat* (although it also applies to any rental property), and more recently also use the terms *unit* or *apartment*.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Australia, a 'unit' refers to flats, apartments or even semi-detached houses.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Australia, the terms "unit", "flat" and "apartment" are largely used interchangeably.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Newer high-rise buildings are more often marketed as "apartments", as the term "flats" carries colloquial connotations.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The term condominium or condo is rarely used in Australia despite attempts by developers to market it.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Malaysian English, *flat* often denotes a housing block of two rooms with walk-up, no lift, without facilities, typically five stories tall, and with outdoor parking space, while *apartment* is more generic and may also include luxury condominiums.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Japanese English loanwords (*Wasei-eigo*), the term *apartment* (アパート *apaato*) is used for lower-income housing and *mansion* (マンション *manshon*) is used for high-end apartments; but both terms refer to what English-speakers regard as an apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This use of the term *mansion* has a parallel with British English's *mansion block*, a term denoting prestigious apartment buildings from the Victorian and Edwardian, which usually feature an ornate facade and large, high-ceilinged flats with period features.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] *Danchi* is the Japanese word for a large cluster of apartment buildings of a particular style and design, typically built as public housing by government authorities.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The smallest self-contained apartments are referred to as studio, efficiency or bachelor apartments in the US and Canada, or studio flat in the UK.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] These units usually consist of a large single main room which acts as the living room, dining room and bedroom combined and usually also includes kitchen facilities, with a separate bathroom.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Korea, the term "one room" (*wonroom*) refers to a studio apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A bedsit is a UK variant on single room accommodation: a bed-sitting room, probably without cooking facilities, with a shared bathroom.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A bedsit is not self-contained and so is not an apartment or flat as this article uses the terms; it forms part of what the UK government calls a house in multiple occupation.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The American variant of the bedsit is the single room occupancy.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Merriam-Webster defines a garden apartment in American English as "a multiple-unit low-rise dwelling having considerable lawn or garden space." The apartment buildings are often arranged around courtyards that are open at one end.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Such a garden apartment shares some characteristics of a townhouse: each apartment has its own building entrance, or shares that entrance via a staircase and lobby that adjoins other units immediately above and/or below it.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Unlike a townhouse, each apartment occupies only one level.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Such garden apartment buildings are almost never more than three stories high, since they typically lack elevators.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] However, the first "garden apartment" buildings in New York, US, built in the early 1900s, were constructed five stories high.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some garden apartment buildings place a one-car garage under each apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The interior grounds are often landscaped.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Chicago, a garden apartment refers to a basement apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The *Oxford English Dictionary* defines the use of "garden flat" in British English as "a basement or ground-floor flat with a view of and access to a garden or lawn", although its citations acknowledge that the reference to a garden may be illusory.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] "Garden flat" can serve simply as a euphemism for a basement.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The large Georgian or Victorian townhouse was built with an excavated subterranean space around its front known as an area, often surrounded by cast iron railings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This lowest floor housed the kitchen, the main place of work for the servants, with a "tradesman's entrance" via the area stairs.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This "lower ground floor" (another euphemism) has proven ideal for conversion to a self-contained "garden flat".
[src:emergency-light/apartment] One American term for this arrangement is an English basement.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Generally on the lowest (below ground) floor of a building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A unit in the attic of a building and usually converted from domestic servants' quarters.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] These apartments are characterized by their sloping walls, which can restrict the usable space; the resultant stair climb in buildings that do not have elevators and the sloping walls can make garret apartments less desirable than units on lower floors.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] However, because these apartments are located on the top floors of their buildings, they can offer the best views and are quieter because of the lack of upstairs neighbours.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Canada these are commonly located below the main house and are therefore "basement suites".
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Another term is an "accessory dwelling unit", which may be part of the main house, or a free-standing structure in its grounds.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] It also allows for apartments, even when they are accessed by a corridor, to have windows on both sides of the building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A maisonette could encompass Tyneside flats, pairs of single-storey flats within a two-storey terrace.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Their distinctive feature is their use of two separate front doors onto the street, each door leading to a single flat.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] "Maisonette" could also stretch to cottage flats, also known as 'four-in-a-block flats', a style of housing common in Scotland.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The vast majority of apartments are on one level, hence "flat".
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some, however, have two storeys joined internally by stairs, just like many houses.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] One term for this is "maisonette", as above.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some housing in the United Kingdom, both public and private, was designed as scissor section flats.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] On a grander level, penthouses may have more than one storey to emphasise the idea of space and luxury.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Two-storey units in new construction are sometimes referred to as "townhouses" in some countries (though not usually in Britain).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] "Duplex" refers to two separate units horizontally adjacent, with a common demising wall, or vertically adjacent, with a floor-ceiling assembly.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Groups of more than two units have corresponding names (Triplex, etc.).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Those buildings that have a third storey are known as triplexes.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the United States, regional forms have developed, see vernacular architecture.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Milwaukee, a Polish flat or "raised cottage" is a small house that has been lifted up to accommodate a basement floor housing a separate apartment, then set down again, thus becoming a modest pair of dwellings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the Sun Belt, boxy small apartment buildings called dingbats, often with carports below, sprang up from the 1950s.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the United Kingdom the term *duplex* is usually applied to an apartment with two storeys (with an internal staircase), neither of which is located at ground level.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Such homes are frequently found in low-cost rental housing, in apartment blocks constructed by local authorities, or above street-level retail units, where they may be occupied by the occupier of the retail unit or rented out separately.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Buildings containing two dwellings with a common vertical wall are known as *semi-detached*, or colloquially *semis*.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This form of construction is very common and built as such rather than being a later conversion.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This type of apartment developed in the US during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The term initially described a living space created within a former industrial building, usually 19th century.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] These large apartments found favor with artists and musicians wanting accommodation in large cities (New York for example) and are related to unused buildings in the decaying parts of such cities being occupied illegally by people squatting.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] These loft apartments were usually located in former high-rise warehouses and factories left vacant after town planning rules and economic conditions in the mid 20th century changed.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The resulting apartments created a new bohemian lifestyle and were arranged in a completely different way from most urban living spaces, often including workshops and art studio spaces.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] As the supply of old buildings of a suitable nature has dried up, developers have responded by constructing new buildings in the same aesthetic with varying degrees of success.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] An industrial, warehouse, or commercial space converted to an apartment is commonly called a *loft*, although some modern lofts are built by design.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A penthouse is an apartment usually located on the top floor of a high-rise apartment building.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This type of house has exclusive features like private elevators, landscaped terraces, and high ceilings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Russia, a communal apartment («коммуналка») is a room with a shared kitchen and bath.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A typical arrangement is a cluster of five or so room-apartments with a common kitchen and bathroom and separate front doors, occupying a floor in a pre-Revolutionary mansion.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Traditionally a room is owned by the government and assigned to a family on a semi-permanent basis.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A serviced apartment is any-size space for residential living that includes regular maid and cleaning services provided by the rental agent.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Serviced apartments or serviced flats developed in the early part of the 20th century and were briefly fashionable in the 1920s and 30s.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] They are intended to combine the best features of luxury and self-contained apartments, often being an adjunct of a hotel.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Like guests semi-permanently installed in a luxury hotel, residents could enjoy the additional facilities such as house keeping, laundry, catering and other services if and when desired.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A feature of these apartment blocks was quite glamorous interiors with lavish bathrooms but no kitchen or laundry spaces in each flat.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This style of living became very fashionable as many upper-class people found they could not afford as many live-in staff after the First World War and revelled in a "lock-up and leave" life style that serviced apartment hotels supplied.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some buildings have been subsequently renovated with standard facilities in each apartment, but serviced apartment hotel complexes continue to be constructed.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Recently a number of hotels have supplemented their traditional business model with serviced apartment wings, creating privately owned areas within their buildings - either freehold or leasehold.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartments may be available for rent furnished, with furniture, or unfurnished into which a tenant moves in with his own furniture.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Serviced apartments, intended to be convenient for shorter stays, include soft furnishings and kitchen utensils, and maid service.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Laundry facilities may reside in a common area accessible to all building tenants, or each apartment may have its own facilities.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Depending on when the building was built and its design, utilities such as water, heating, and electricity may be common for all of the apartments, or separate for each apartment and billed separately to each tenant.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] (Many areas in the US have ruled it illegal to split a water bill among all the tenants, especially if a pool is on the premises.) Outlets for connection to telephones are typically included in apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Telephone service is optional and is almost always billed separately from the rent payments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Cable television and similar amenities also cost extra.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Parking space(s), air conditioning, and extra storage space may or may not be included with an apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Rental leases often limit the maximum number of residents in each apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] On or around the ground floor of the apartment building, a series of mailboxes are typically kept in a location accessible to the public and, thus, to the mail carrier.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Every unit typically gets its own mailbox with individual keys to it.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some very large apartment buildings with a full-time staff may take mail from the carrier and provide mail-sorting service.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Near the mailboxes or some other location accessible by outsiders, a buzzer (equivalent to a doorbell) may be available for each individual unit.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In smaller apartment buildings such as two- or three-flats, or even four-flats, rubbish is often disposed of in trash containers similar to those used at houses.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In larger buildings, rubbish is often collected in a common trash bin or dumpster.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] For cleanliness or minimizing noise, many lessors will place restrictions on tenants regarding smoking or keeping pets in an apartment.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In more urban areas, apartments close to the downtown (British English town- or city-centre area have the benefits of proximity to jobs and/or public transportation.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] However prices per square foot/meter are often much higher than in suburban areas.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Moving up in size from studio flats are one-bedroom apartments, which contain a bedroom enclosed from the other rooms of the apartment, usually by an internal door.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This is followed by two-bedroom, three-bedroom, etc.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartments with more than three bedrooms are rare.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Small apartments often have only one entrance.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Large apartments often have two entrances, perhaps a door in the front and another in the back, or from an underground or otherwise attached parking structure.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Depending on the building design, the entrance doors may be connected directly to the outside or to a common area inside, such as a hallway or a lobby.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Puebloan peoples of what is now the Southwestern United States have constructed large, multi-room dwellings, some comprising more than 900 rooms, since the 10th century.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the Classic Period Mesoamerican city of Teotihuacan, apartments were not only the standard means of housing the city's population of over 200,000 inhabitants, but show a remarkably even wealth distribution for the entire city, even by contemporary standards.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Furthermore, the apartments were inhabited by the general populace as a whole, in contrast to other Pre-Modern societies, where apartments were limited to housing the lower class members of the society, as with the somewhat contemporary Roman insulae.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In ancient Rome, the insulae (singular *insula*) were large apartment buildings where the lower and middle classes of Romans dwelled.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The floor at ground level was used for tabernae, shops and businesses, with living space on the higher floors.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Insulae in Rome and other imperial cities reached up to ten or more stories, some with more than 200 stairs.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Several emperors, beginning with Augustus (r.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] 30 BC – 14 AD), attempted to establish limits of 20–25 m for multi-story buildings, but met with only limited success.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The lower floors were typically occupied by either shops or wealthy families, while the upper stories were rented out to the lower classes.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Surviving Oxyrhynchus Papyri indicate that seven-story buildings even existed in provincial towns, such as in 3rd century Hermopolis in Roman Egypt.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] During the medieval Arabic-Islamic period, the Egyptian capital of Fustat (Old Cairo) housed many high-rise residential buildings, some seven stories tall that could reportedly accommodate hundreds of people.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the 10th century, Al-Muqaddasi described them as resembling minarets, and stated that the majority of Fustat's population lived in these multi-story apartment buildings, each one housing more than 200 people.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the 11th century, Nasir Khusraw described some of these apartment buildings rising up to fourteen stories, with roof gardens on the top story complete with ox-drawn water wheels for irrigating them.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] By the 16th century, the current Cairo also had high-rise apartment buildings, in which the two lower floors were for commercial and storage purposes and the multiple stories above them were rented out to tenants.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] High-rise apartment buildings were built in the Yemeni city of Shibam in the 16th century.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The houses of Shibam are all made out of mud bricks, but about 500 of them are tower houses, which rise 5 to 11 stories high, with each floor having one or two apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Shibam has been called "Manhattan of the desert".
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some of them were over 100 feet (30 m) high, thus being the tallest mudbrick apartment buildings in the world to this day.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Hakka people in southern China adopted communal living structures designed to be easily defensible, in the form of Weilongwu (围龙屋) and Tulou (土楼).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The latter are large, enclosed and fortified earth buildings, between three and five stories high and housing up to eighty families.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In London, by the time of the 2011 census, 52 per cent of all homes were flats.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many of these were built as Georgian or Victorian houses and subsequently divided up.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many others were built as council flats.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many tower blocks were built after the Second World War.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] A number of these have been demolished and replaced with low-rise buildings or housing estates.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the concept of the flat was slow to catch on amongst the British middle classes, which generally followed the north European standard of single-family houses dating far back into history.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Those who lived in flats were assumed to be lower class and somewhat itinerant, renting for example a "flat above a shop" as part of a lease agreement for a tradesman.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In London and most of Britain, everyone who could afford to do so occupied an entire house—even if this was a small terraced house—while the working poor continued to rent rooms in often overcrowded properties, with one (or more) families per room.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] During the last quarter of the 19th century, as wealth increased, ideas began to change.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Both urban growth and the increase in population meant that more imaginative housing concepts would be needed if the middle and upper classes were to maintain a *pied-à-terre* in the capital.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The traditional London town house was becoming increasingly expensive to maintain.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] For bachelors and unmarried women in particular, the idea of renting a modern mansion flat became increasingly popular.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Scotland, the term "tenement" lacks the pejorative connotations it carries elsewhere and refers simply to any block of flats sharing a common central staircase and lacking an elevator, particularly those constructed before 1919.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The staircase is informally called a "close" after the historic word for an alleyway.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Tenements were, and continue to be, inhabited by a wide range of social classes and income groups.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Tenements today are bought by a wide range of social types, including young professionals, older retirees, and by absentee landlords, often for rental to students after they leave halls of residence managed by their institution.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Tenement House is a historic house museum operated by the National Trust for Scotland which offers an insight into the lifestyle of tenement dwellers as it was generations ago.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] During the 19th century, tenements became the predominant type of new housing in Scotland's industrial cities, although they were very common in the Old Town in Edinburgh from the 15th century, where they reached ten or eleven stories and in one case fourteen stories.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Built of sandstone or granite, Scottish tenements are usually three to five stories in height, with two to four flats on each floor.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] (In contrast, industrial cities in England tended to favour "back-to-back" terraces of brick.) Scottish tenements are constructed in terraces, and each entrance within a block is referred to as a *close* or *stair*—both referring to the shared passageway to the individual flats.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Flights of stairs and landings are generally designated common areas, and residents traditionally took turns to sweep clean the floors and, in Aberdeen in particular, took turns to make use of shared laundry facilities in the "back green" (garden or yard).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] It is now more common for cleaning of the common ways to be contracted out through a managing agent or "factor".
[src:emergency-light/apartment] They were replaced by high-rise blocks that, within a couple of decades, became notorious for crime and poverty.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Glasgow Corporation made many efforts to improve the situation, most successfully with the City Improvement Trust, which cleared the slums of the old town, replacing them with what they thought of as a traditional high street, which remains an imposing townscape.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] (The City Halls and the Cleland Testimonial were part of this scheme.) National government help was given following World War I when Housing Acts sought to provide "homes fit for heroes".
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Garden suburb areas, based on English models, such as Knightswood, were set up.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] These proved too expensive, so a modern tenement, three stories high, slate roofed and built of reconstituted stone, was re-introduced and a slum clearance programme initiated to clear areas such as the Calton and the Garngad.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] After World War II, more ambitious plans, known as the Bruce Plan, were made for the complete evacuation of slums for modern mid-rise housing developments on the outskirts of the city.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] However, the central government refused to fund the plans, preferring instead to depopulate the city to a series of New Towns.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Again, economic considerations meant that many of the planned "New Town" amenities were never built in these areas.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] These housing estates, known as "schemes", came therefore to be widely regarded as unsuccessful; many, such as Castlemilk, were just dormitories well away from the centre of the city with no amenities, such as shops and public houses ("deserts with windows", as Billy Connolly once put it).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] High-rise living too started off with bright ambition—the Moss Heights, built in the 1950s, are still desirable—but fell prey to later economic pressure.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many of the later tower blocks were poorly designed and cheaply built and their anonymity caused some social problems.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The demolition of the tower blocks in order to build modern housing schemes has in some cases led to a re-interpretations of the tenement.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In 1970, a team from Strathclyde University demonstrated that the old tenements had been basically sound, and could be given new life with replumbing providing modern kitchens and bathrooms.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Corporation acted on this principle for the first time in 1973 at the *Old Swan Corner*, Pollokshaws.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Thereafter, *Housing Action Areas* were set up to renovate so-called slums.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Later, privately owned tenements benefited from government help in "stone cleaning", revealing a honey-coloured sandstone behind the presumed "grey" tenemental facades.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The policy of tenement demolition is now considered to have been short-sighted, wasteful and largely unsuccessful.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many of Glasgow's worst tenements were refurbished into desirable accommodation in the 1970s and 1980s and the policy of demolition is considered to have destroyed fine examples of a "universally admired architectural" style.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Glasgow Housing Association took ownership of the public housing stock from the city council on 7 March 2003, and has begun a £96 million clearance and demolition programme to clear and demolish many of the high-rise flats.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In 1839, the first New York City tenement was built, and soon they became breeding grounds for outlaws, juvenile delinquents, and organized crime.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Tenements, or their slum landlords, were also known for their price gouging rent.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many campaigners, such as Upton Sinclair and Jacob Riis, pushed for reforms in tenement dwellings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] As a result, the New York State Tenement House Act was passed in 1901 to improve the conditions.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Truman signed the Housing Act of 1949 to clean slums and reconstruct housing units for the poor.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The Dakota (1884) was one of the first luxury apartment buildings in New York City.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The majority, however, remained tenements.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Some significant developments in architectural design of apartment buildings came out of the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Among them were groundbreaking designs in Chicago: the 860-880 Lake Shore Drive Apartments (1951), Marina City (1964) and Lake Point Tower (1968).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the United States, "tenement" is a label usually applied to the less expensive, more basic rental apartment buildings in older sections of large cities.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many of these apartment buildings are "walk-ups" without an elevator, and some have shared bathing facilities, though this is becoming less common.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The slang term "dingbat" is used to describe cheap urban apartment buildings from the 1950s and 1960s with unique and often wacky façades to differentiate themselves within a full block of apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] They are often built on stilts, and with parking underneath.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartments were popular in Canada, particularly in urban centres like Vancouver, Toronto, Ottawa, Montreal, and Hamilton in the 1950s to 1970s.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] By the 1980s, many multi-unit buildings were being constructed as condominiums instead of apartments—both are now very common.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Toronto and Vancouver, high-rise apartments and condominiums have been spread around the city, giving even the major suburbs a skyline.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The robustness of the condo markets in Toronto and Vancouver are based on the lack of land availability.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The average capitalization rate in the Greater Toronto Area for Q3 2015 hit its lowest level in 30 years: in Q3 2015 it stood at 3.75 per cent, down from 4.2 per cent in Q2 2015 and down almost 50 per cent from the 6.3 per cent posted in Q3 2010.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartment buildings in Australia are typically managed by a body corporate in which owners pay a monthly fee to provide for maintenance of common premises.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Many apartments are owned through strata title.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Australian legislation enforces a minimum 2.4 m floor-ceiling height which differentiates apartment buildings from office buildings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Australia has a relatively recent history in apartment buildings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Terrace houses were the early response to density development, though the majority of Australians lived in fully detached houses.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartments of any kind were legislated against in the Parliament of Queensland as part of the Undue Subdivision of Land Prevention Act 1885.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The earliest apartment buildings were in the major cities of Sydney and Melbourne as the response to fast rising land values–both cities are home to the two oldest surviving apartment buildings in the country, Kingsclere in Potts Point, and The Canterbury Flats in St Kilda.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Melbourne Mansions on Collins Street, Melbourne (now demolished), built in 1906 for mostly wealthy residents is believed by many to be the earliest.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Today the oldest surviving self-contained apartment buildings are in the St Kilda area including the Fawkner Mansions (1910), Majestic Mansions (1912 as a boarding house) and the Canterbury (1914—the oldest surviving buildings contained flats).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Kingsclere, built in 1912 is believed to be the earliest apartment building in Sydney and still survives.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] During the interwar years, apartment building continued in inner Melbourne (particularly in areas such as St Kilda and South Yarra), Sydney (particularly in areas such as Potts Point, Darlinghust and Kings Cross) and in Brisbane (in areas such as New Farm, Fortitude Valley and Spring Hill).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Post–World War II, with the Australian Dream apartment buildings went out of vogue and flats were seen as accommodation only for the poor.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Walk-up flats (without a lift) of two to three stories however were common in the middle suburbs of cities for lower income groups.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The main exceptions were Sydney and the Gold Coast, Queensland where apartment development continued for more than half a century.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Sydney a limited geography and highly sought after waterfront views (Sydney Harbour and beaches such as Bondi) made apartment living socially acceptable.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Since the 1960s, these cities maintained much higher population densities than the rest of Australia through the acceptance of apartment buildings.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In other cities, apartment building was almost solely restricted to public housing.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Public housing in Australia was common in the larger cities, particularly in Melbourne (by the Housing Commission of Victoria) where a number of high-rise housing commission flats were built between the 1950s and 1970s by successive governments as part of an urban renewal program.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Areas affected included Fitzroy, Flemington, Collingwood, Carlton, Richmond and Prahran.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Similar projects were run in Sydney's lower socio-economic areas like Redfern.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In the 1980s, modern apartment buildings sprang up in riverside locations in Brisbane (along the Brisbane River) and Perth (along the Swan River).
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In Melbourne, in the 1990s, a trend began for apartment buildings without the requirement of spectacular views.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] As a continuation of the gentrification of the inner city, a fashion became New York "loft" style apartments (see above) and a large stock of old warehouses and old abandoned office buildings in and around the central business district became the target of developers.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The trend of adaptive reuse extended to conversion of old churches and schools.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Similar warehouse conversions and gentrification began in Brisbane suburbs such as Teneriffe, Queensland and Fortitude Valley and in Sydney in areas such as Ultimo.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] As the supply of buildings for conversion ran out, reproduction and modern high-rise apartments followed.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This was particularly the case in Melbourne thanks to official planning policies (Postcode 3000), making the CBD the fastest growing, population wise in the country.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartment building in the Melbourne metropolitan area has also escalated with the advent of the Melbourne 2030 planning policy.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Urban renewal areas like Docklands, Southbank, St Kilda Road and Port Melbourne are now predominantly apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] There has also been a sharp increase in the number of student apartment buildings in areas such as Carlton in Melbourne.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Despite their size, other smaller cities including Canberra, Darwin, Townsville, Cairns, Newcastle, Wollongong, Adelaide and Geelong have begun building apartments in the 2000s.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Today, residential buildings such as the Eureka Tower and Q1 are among the tallest in the country.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] As of 2019, a majority of Koreans live in apartments.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Since the 1980s, the number of apartment residents has soared, and as the number of apartments has steadily increased, apartments have become a representative form of residence where more than half of the Korean population resides.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] It is the most common house in small and medium-sized cities in Korea, and even these days, apartments are quite visible in rural areas such as remote areas.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] This is because small and medium-sized construction companies have technology, but they lack the capital to build large complexes in large cities.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The better the location, the more expensive the apartment is, and the more expensive the apartment complex built by a large construction company and with a large number of households.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Also, even the same type of flat in the same complex is not all of the same price.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Due to problems such as the right to sunlight and prospects, the low-rise households on the first and third floors are generally the cheapest, and the higher they go, the more expensive they become.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] In addition, the price varies depending on other conditions such as the viewing area and the direction of the house, such as south, east, west, and north.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] The upper floors with a south-facing view are the most expensive.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] Apartment sales and lease prices are actually the largest and most stable assets owned by a middle-class family in Korea, symbolizing the social status of a family, which forms a class and determines life satisfaction.
[src:emergency-light/apartment] For this reason, the Korean people have no choice but to react very sensitively to apartment prices.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:emergency-light/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:emergency-light/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:emergency-light/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:emergency-light/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Today there are numerous types of automatic fire suppression systems and standards for each one.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Systems are as diverse as the many applications.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In general, however, automatic fire suppression systems fall into two categories: *engineered* and *pre-engineered* systems.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] By definition, an automatic fire suppression system can operate without human intervention.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] To do so it must possess a means of detection, actuation and delivery.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In many systems, detection is accomplished by mechanical or electrical means.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Mechanical detection uses fusible-link or thermo-bulb detectors.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] These detectors are designed to separate at a specific temperature and release tension on a release mechanism.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Electrical detection uses heat detectors equipped with self-restoring, normally-open contacts which close when a predetermined temperature is reached.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Remote and local manual operation is also possible.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Actuation usually involves either a pressurized fluid and a release valve, or in some cases an electric pump.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Delivery is accomplished by means of piping and nozzles.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Nozzle design is specific to the agent used and coverage desired.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Water is the most prevalent fire suppression agent in use worldwide.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] However, the use of water does have some limitations, which can range from inadequate supplies (particularly in less developed regions) to operations and processes which are highly susceptible to water damage.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In some cases, certain contents or processes (such as water-reactive chemicals or metals, molten materials, etc.) are truly incompatible with water; water discharge could lead to explosion.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Despite their effectiveness, chemical fire extinguishing agents are not without disadvantages.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In the early 20th century, carbon tetrachloride was extensively used as a dry cleaning solvent, a refrigerant and as a fire extinguishing agent.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In time, it was found carbon tetrachloride could lead to severe health effects.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] From the mid-1960s Halon 1301 was the industry standard for protecting high-value assets from the threat of fire.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301 had many benefits as a fire suppression agent; it is fast-acting, safe for assets and required minimal storage space.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301's major drawbacks are that it depletes atmospheric ozone and is potentially harmful to humans.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Since 1987, some 191 nations have signed The Montreal Protocol on Substances That Deplete the Ozone Layer.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] The Protocol is an international treaty designed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production of a number of substances believed to be responsible for ozone depletion.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Among these were halogenated hydrocarbons often used in fire suppression.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] As a result, manufacturers have focused on alternatives to Halon 1301 and Halon 1211 (halogenated hydrocarbons).
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] A number of countries have also taken steps to mandate the removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Most notably these include Germany and Australia, the first two countries in the world to require this action.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In both of these countries complete removal of installed Halon systems has been completed except for a very few essential-use applications.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] The European Union is currently undergoing a similar mandated removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire extinguisher patent was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire sprinkler system was patented by H.W.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] But the first practical automatic sprinkler system was invented in 1874 by Henry S.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] He installed the system in a piano factory he owned.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Since the early 1990s manufacturers have successfully developed safe and effective Halon alternatives.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] These include DuPont's FM-200, American Pacific's Halotron, FirePro's FPC Compound, Plumis’ Automist and 3M's Novec 1230 Fire Protection Fluid.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Generally, the Halon replacement agents available today fall into two broad categories, in-kind (gaseous extinguishing agents) or not in-kind (alternative technologies).
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] In-kind gaseous agents generally fall into two further categories, halocarbons and inert gases.
[src:emergency-light/automatic-fire-suppression] Not in-kind alternatives include such options as water mist or the use of early warning smoke detection systems.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] A **car**, or an **automobile**, is a motor vehicle with wheels.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Most definitions of cars state that they run primarily on roads, seat 1-8 people, have four wheels, and mainly transport people rather than cargo.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] There are over 1.6 billion cars in use worldwide as of 2025.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The French inventor Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot built the first steam-powered road vehicle in 1769, while the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed and constructed the first internal combustion-powered automobile in 1808.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The modern car—a practical, marketable automobile for everyday use—was invented in 1886, when the German inventor Carl Benz patented his Benz Patent-Motorwagen.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Commercial cars became widely available during the 20th century.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The 1901 Oldsmobile Curved Dash and the 1908 Ford Model T, both American cars, are widely considered the first mass-produced and mass-affordable cars, respectively.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars were rapidly adopted in the US, where they replaced horse-drawn carriages.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In Europe and other parts of the world, demand for automobiles did not increase until after World War II.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In the 21st century, car usage is still increasing rapidly, especially in China, India, and other newly industrialised countries.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars have controls for driving, parking, passenger comfort, and a variety of lamps.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Over the decades, additional features and controls have been added to vehicles, making them progressively more complex.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] These include rear-reversing cameras, air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Most cars in use in the early 2020s are propelled by an internal combustion engine, fueled by the combustion of fossil fuels.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Electric cars, which were invented early in the history of the car, became commercially available in the 2000s and widespread in the 2020s.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The transition from fossil-fuel-powered cars to electric cars is a central feature of most climate change mitigation scenarios.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] There are costs and benefits to car use.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The costs to the individual include acquiring the vehicle, interest payments (if the car is financed), repairs and maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The costs to society include resources used to produce cars and fuel, maintaining roads, land-use, road congestion, air pollution, noise pollution, public health, and disposing of the vehicle at the end of its life.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Traffic collisions are the largest cause of injury-related deaths worldwide.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Personal benefits include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Societal benefits include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation from the automotive industry, transportation provision, and societal wellbeing from leisure and travel opportunities.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] People's ability to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for society.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The English word *car* is believed to originate from Latin *carrus*/*carrum* "wheeled vehicle" or (via Old North French) Middle English **carre** "two-wheeled cart", both of which in turn derive from Gaulish **karros** "chariot".
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It originally referred to any wheeled horse-drawn vehicle, such as a cart, carriage, or wagon.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The word also occurs in other Celtic languages.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] "Motor car", attested from 1895, is the usual formal term in British English.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] "Autocar", a variant likewise attested from 1895 and literally meaning "self-propelled car", is now considered archaic.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] "Horseless carriage" is attested from 1895.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] "Automobile", a classical compound derived from Ancient Greek **autós** (αὐτός) "self" and Latin **mobilis** "movable", entered English from French and was first adopted by the Automobile Club of Great Britain in 1897.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It fell out of favour in Britain and is now used chiefly in North America, where the abbreviated form "auto" commonly appears as an adjective in compound formations like "auto industry" and "auto mechanic".
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1649, Hans Hautsch of Nuremberg built a clockwork-driven carriage.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The first steam-powered vehicle was designed by Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish member of a Jesuit mission in China around 1672.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It was a 65-centimetre-long (26 in) scale-model toy for the Kangxi Emperor that was unable to carry a driver or a passenger.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It is not known with certainty if Verbiest's model was successfully built or run.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Nicolas-Joseph Cugnot is widely credited with building the first full-scale, self-propelled mechanical vehicle in about 1769; he created a steam-powered tricycle.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] He also constructed two steam tractors for the French Army, one of which is preserved in the French National Conservatory of Arts and Crafts.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] His inventions were limited by problems with water supply and maintaining steam pressure.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1801, Richard Trevithick built and demonstrated his Puffing Devil road locomotive, believed by many to be the first demonstration of a steam-powered road vehicle.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It was unable to maintain sufficient steam pressure for long periods and was of little practical use.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The development of external combustion (also known as steam) engines is detailed in the history of the car.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Still, it is often treated separately from the development of cars in their modern understanding.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] A variety of steam-powered road vehicles were used during the first part of the 19th century, including steam cars, steam buses, phaetons, and steam rollers.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In the United Kingdom, sentiment against them led to the Locomotive Acts of 1865.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1807, Nicéphore Niépce and his brother Claude created what was probably the world's first internal combustion engine (which they called a Pyréolophore), but installed it in a boat on the river Saone in France.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Coincidentally, in 1807, the Swiss inventor François Isaac de Rivaz designed his own "de Rivaz internal combustion engine", and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to be powered by such an engine.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The Niépces' Pyréolophore was fuelled by a mixture of Lycopodium powder (dried spores of the Lycopodium plant), finely crushed coal dust, and resin that were mixed with oil, whereas de Rivaz used a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Neither design was successful, as was the case with others, such as Samuel Brown, Samuel Morey, and Etienne Lenoir, who each built vehicles (usually adapted carriages or carts) powered by internal combustion engines.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In November 1881, French inventor Gustave Trouvé demonstrated a three-wheeled car powered by electricity at the International Exposition of Electricity.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Several other German engineers, including Gottlieb Daimler, Wilhelm Maybach, Siegfried Marcus, and Carl Benz were also working on cars and engines at about the same time.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1879, Benz was granted a patent for a stationary engine.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] He had long dreamed of applying the internal combustion engine to produce a horseless carriage and began work on it in 1884.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1885 he produced his first prototype car, the Benz Patent-Motorwagen Nr.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] On 29 January 1886 he applied for a patent for it, which was granted on 2 November of that year.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Benz further developed the Patent-Motorwagen, and had sufficient confidence in this to drive into Mannheim and have his vehicle written up in the *Neue Badische Landeszeitung* of 4 June 1886.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Benz' first production car, the Patent-Motorwagen Model 2, was produced in single-digit numbers in 1887–88.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Frenchman Émile Roger, already producing Benz engines under license, had added the Benz car to his product line in 1888.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Perhaps 60 of the Model 3 were produced between 1889 and 1893, the majority assembled in Paris from kits by Émile Roger.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Many historians consider Benz' advances so significant that they largely credit him as the inventor of the car and regard his 1886 patent as the birth of the modern car.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In August 1888, Bertha Benz, the wife and business partner of Carl Benz, undertook the first road trip by an internal combustion engine car, to prove the road-worthiness of her husband's invention.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1896, Carl Benz designed and patented the first internal-combustion flat engine, called *boxermotor*.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] During the last years of the 19th century, Benz was the largest car company in the world with 572 units produced in 1899 and, because of its size, Benz & Cie. became a joint-stock company.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The first motor car in central Europe and one of the first factory-made cars in the world was produced by the Czech company Nesselsdorfer Wagenbau (later renamed to Tatra) in 1897, the Präsident automobil.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Daimler and Maybach founded Daimler Motoren Gesellschaft (DMG) in Cannstatt in 1890, and sold their first car in 1892 under the brand name *Daimler*.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It was a horse-drawn stagecoach built by another manufacturer, which they retrofitted with an engine of their design.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] By 1895, about 30 vehicles had been built by Daimler and Maybach, either at the Daimler works or at the Hotel Hermann, where they set up shop after disputes with their backers.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Benz, Maybach, and the Daimler team seem to have been unaware of each other's early work.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] They never worked together; by the time of the merger of the two companies, Daimler and Maybach were no longer part of DMG.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Daimler died in 1900, and later that year, Maybach designed an engine named *Daimler-Mercedes* that was installed in a specially ordered model built to specifications set by Emil Jellinek.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] This was a limited production run of vehicles for Jellinek to race and market in his country.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Two years later, in 1902, a new model of the DMG car was produced and named Mercedes after the Maybach engine, which generated 35 hp.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Maybach left DMG shortly thereafter and opened his own business.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Rights to the *Daimler* brand name were sold to other manufacturers.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1890, Émile Levassor (who had bought a Benz Patent-Motorwagen Model 2 in 1888) and Armand Peugeot of France began producing vehicles with Daimler engines, and so laid the foundation of the automotive industry in France.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1891, Auguste Doriot and his Peugeot colleague Louis Rigoulot completed the longest trip by a petrol-driven vehicle when their self-designed and built Daimler-powered Peugeot Type 3 completed 2,100 kilometres (1,300 mi) from Valentigney to Paris and Brest and back again.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] They were attached to the first Paris–Brest–Paris bicycle race, but finished six days after the winning cyclist, Charles Terront.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The first design for an American car with a petrol internal combustion engine was made in 1877 by George Selden of Rochester, New York.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Selden applied for a patent for a car in 1879, but the patent application expired because the vehicle was never built.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] After a delay of 16 years and a series of attachments to his application, on 5 November 1895, Selden was granted a US patent (U.S. patent 549,160) for a two-stroke car engine, which hindered, more than encouraged, development of cars in the United States.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] His patent was challenged by Henry Ford and others, and overturned in 1911.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1893, the first running, petrol-driven American car was built and road-tested by the Duryea brothers of Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The first public run of the Duryea Motor Wagon took place on 21 September 1893, on Taylor Street in Metro Center Springfield.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Studebaker, subsidiary of a long-established wagon and coach manufacturer, started to build cars in 1897 and commenced sales of electric vehicles in 1902 and petrol vehicles in 1904.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In Britain, there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success, with Thomas Rickett even attempting a production run in 1860.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Santler from Malvern is recognised by the Veteran Car Club of Great Britain as having made the first petrol-driven car in the country in 1894, followed by Frederick William Lanchester in 1895, but these were both one-offs.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The first production vehicles in Great Britain came from the Daimler Company, a company founded by Harry J.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Lawson in 1896, after purchasing the right to use the name of the engines.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Lawson's company made its first car in 1897, and they bore the name Daimler.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1892, German engineer Rudolf Diesel was granted a patent for a "New Rational Combustion Engine".
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1897, he built the first diesel engine.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Steam-, electric-, and petrol-driven vehicles competed for a few decades, with petrol internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design, only Mazda's version of the Wankel engine has had more than very limited success.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] All in all, it is estimated that over 100,000 patents have contributed to the modern automobile and motorcycle.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Large-scale, production-line manufacturing of affordable cars was started by Ransom Olds in 1901 at his Oldsmobile factory in Lansing, Michigan, and based upon stationary assembly line techniques pioneered by Marc Isambard Brunel at the Portsmouth Block Mills, England, in 1802.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The assembly line style of mass production and interchangeable parts had been pioneered in the US by Thomas Blanchard in 1821, at the Springfield Armory in Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] This concept was greatly expanded by Henry Ford, beginning in 1913 with the world's first *moving* assembly line for cars at the Highland Park Ford Plant.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] As a result, Ford's cars came off the line in 15-minute intervals, much faster than previous methods, increasing productivity eightfold while using less labour (from 12.5 manhours to 1 hour 33 minutes).
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It was so successful, paint became a bottleneck.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Only Japan black would dry fast enough, forcing the company to drop the variety of colours available before 1913, until fast-drying Duco lacquer was developed in 1926.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] This is the source of Ford's apocryphal remark, "any color as long as it's black".
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 1914, an assembly line worker could buy a Model T with four months' pay.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Ford's complex safety procedures—especially assigning each worker to a specific location rather than allowing them to roam—dramatically reduced injury rates.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The combination of high wages and high efficiency is called "Fordism" and was copied by most major industries.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The efficiency gains from the assembly line also coincided with the US's economic rise.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The assembly line forced workers to move at a certain pace with very repetitive motions, which led to more output per worker, while other countries used less productive methods.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In the automotive industry, its success was dominant and quickly spread worldwide, with the founding of Ford France and Ford Britain in 1911, Ford Denmark in 1923, and Ford Germany in 1925; in 1921, Citroën was the first native European manufacturer to adopt the production method.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Soon, companies had to have assembly lines or risk going bankrupt; by 1930, 250 companies that did not have assembly lines disappeared.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The development of automotive technology was rapid, due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Key developments included electric ignition and the electric self-starter (both by Charles Kettering, for the Cadillac Motor Company in 1910–1911), independent suspension, and four-wheel brakes.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Since the 1920s, nearly all cars have been mass-produced to meet market needs, so marketing plans have often heavily influenced car design.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company, called the General Motors Companion Make Program, so that buyers could "move up" as their fortunes improved.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Reflecting the rapid pace of change, makers shared parts with one another, resulting in lower costs across all price ranges.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Most British small-car assemblers, from Abbey to Xtra, had gone under.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Citroën did the same in France, coming to cars in 1919; between them and other cheap cars in reply such as Renault's 10CV and Peugeot's 5CV, they produced 550,000 cars in 1925, and Mors, Hurtu, and others could not compete.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Germany's first mass-manufactured car, the Opel 4PS *Laubfrosch* (Tree Frog), came off the line at Rüsselsheim in 1924, soon making Opel the top car builder in Germany, with 37.5 per cent of the market.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In Japan, car production was very limited before World War II.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Only a handful of companies produced vehicles in limited numbers, and these were small, three-wheeled for commercial use, like Daihatsu, or the result of partnerships with European companies, like Isuzu building the Wolseley A-9 in 1922.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Mitsubishi was also partnered with Fiat and built the Mitsubishi Model A based on a Fiat vehicle.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Toyota, Nissan, Suzuki, Mazda, and Honda began as companies producing non-automotive products before the war, then switched to car production in the 1950s.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Kiichiro Toyoda's decision to take Toyoda Loom Works into automobile manufacturing would eventually lead to the formation of Toyota Motor Corporation, the world's largest automobile manufacturer.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Subaru, meanwhile, was formed from a conglomerate of six companies that banded together as Fuji Heavy Industries, as a result of having been broken up under *keiretsu* legislation.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Most cars in use in the mid 2020s run on petrol burnt in an internal combustion engine (ICE).
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Some cities ban older, more polluting petrol-driven cars, and some countries plan to ban sales in the future.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] However, some environmental groups say this phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles must be brought forward to limit climate change.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Production of petrol-fuelled cars peaked in 2017.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Other hydrocarbon fossil fuels also burnt by deflagration (rather than detonation) in ICE cars include diesel, autogas, and CNG.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Removal of fossil fuel subsidies, concerns about oil dependence, tightening environmental laws and restrictions on greenhouse gas emissions are propelling work on alternative power systems for cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] This includes hybrid vehicles, plug-in electric vehicles, and hydrogen vehicles.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] As of 2025 one in four cars sold is electric but, despite rapid growth, less than one in twenty cars on the world's roads were fully electric and plug-in hybrid cars by the end of 2024.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars for racing or speed records have sometimes employed jet or rocket engines, but these are impractical for common use.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Oil consumption has increased rapidly in the 20th and 21st centuries because there are more cars; the 1980s oil glut even fuelled the sales of low-economy vehicles in OECD countries.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In almost all hybrid (even mild hybrid) and pure electric cars, regenerative braking recovers and returns to a battery some energy which would otherwise be wasted by friction brakes getting hot.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Although all cars must have friction brakes (front disc brakes and either disc or drum rear brakes) for emergency stops, regenerative braking improves efficiency, particularly in city driving.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars are equipped with controls for driving, passenger comfort, and safety, normally operated by a combination of feet and hands, and occasionally by voice in 21st-century cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] These controls include a steering wheel, pedals for operating the brakes and controlling the car's speed (and, in a manual transmission car, a clutch pedal), a shift lever or stick for changing gears, and several buttons and dials for turning on lights, ventilation, and other functions.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Modern cars' controls are now standardised, such as the location of the accelerator and brake, but this was not always the case.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Controls are evolving in response to new technologies, for example, the electric car and the integration of mobile communications.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Some of the original controls are no longer required.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] For example, all cars once had controls for the choke valve, clutch, ignition timing, and a crank instead of an electric starter.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] However, new controls have also been added to vehicles, making them more complex.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] These include air conditioning, navigation systems, and in-car entertainment.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Another trend is the replacement of physical knobs and switches with secondary controls, such as touchscreen controls, such as BMW's *iDrive* and Ford's *MyFord Touch*.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Another change is that while early cars' pedals were physically linked to the brake mechanism and throttle, in the early 2020s, cars have increasingly replaced these physical linkages with electronic controls.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] More costly upper-class and luxury cars are equipped with features earlier such as massage seats and collision avoidance systems.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Dedicated automotive fuses and circuit breakers prevent damage from electrical overload.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars are typically fitted with multiple types of lights.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Interior ceiling lights in the car are usually fitted for the driver and passengers.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Some vehicles also have a boot light and, more rarely, an engine compartment light.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] During the late 20th and early 21st century, cars increased in weight due to batteries, modern steel safety cages, anti-lock brakes, airbags, and "more-powerful—if more efficient—engines" and, as of 2019, typically weigh between 1 and 3 tonnes (1.1 and 3.3 short tons; 0.98 and 2.95 long tons).
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Heavier cars are safer for the driver from a crash perspective, but more dangerous for other vehicles and road users.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The weight of a car influences fuel consumption and performance, with more weight resulting in increased fuel consumption and decreased performance.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The Wuling Hongguang Mini EV, a typical city car, weighs about 700 kilograms (1,500 lb).
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Heavier cars include SUVs and extended-length SUVs like the Suburban.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Some places tax heavier cars more: as well as improving pedestrian safety, this can encourage manufacturers to use materials such as recycled aluminium instead of steel.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It has been suggested that one benefit of subsidising charging infrastructure is that cars can use lighter batteries.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Most cars are designed to carry multiple occupants, often with four or five seats.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars with five seats typically seat two passengers in the front and three in the rear.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Full-size cars and large sport utility vehicles can often carry six, seven, or more occupants, depending on seat arrangement.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] On the other hand, sports cars are most often designed with only two seats.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Utility vehicles like pickup trucks combine seating with extra cargo or utility functionality.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The differing needs for passenger capacity and their luggage or cargo space has resulted in the availability of a large variety of body styles to meet individual consumer requirements that include, among others, the sedan/saloon, hatchback, station wagon/estate, coupe, and minivan.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Mary Ward became one of the first documented car fatalities in 1869 in Parsonstown, Ireland, and Henry Bliss one of the US's first pedestrian car casualties in 1899 in New York City.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] There are now standard tests for safety in new cars, such as the Euro and US NCAP tests, and insurance-industry-backed tests by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS).
[src:emergency-light/automobile] However, not all such tests consider the safety of people outside the car, such as drivers of other cars, pedestrians and cyclists.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Some countries are tightening safety regulations for new cars, for example to mandate data recorders and automated braking.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The costs of car usage, which may include the cost of: acquiring the vehicle, repairs and auto maintenance, fuel, depreciation, driving time, parking fees, taxes, and insurance, are weighed against the cost of the alternatives, and the value of the benefits—perceived and real—of vehicle usage.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The benefits may include on-demand transportation, mobility, independence, and convenience, and emergency power.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Societal benefits may include economic benefits, such as job and wealth creation, from car production and maintenance, transportation provision, societal wellbeing derived from leisure and travel opportunities, and revenue generation from the tax opportunities.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The ability of humans to move flexibly from place to place has far-reaching implications for the nature of societies.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Trucks' share of US vehicles produced has tripled since 1975.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Though vehicle fuel efficiency has increased within each category, the overall trend toward less efficient types of vehicles has offset some of the benefits of greater fuel economy and reductions in pollution and carbon dioxide emissions.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Without the shift towards SUVs, energy use per unit distance could have fallen 30% more than it did from 2010 to 2022.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Car production and use have a large number of environmental impacts: it causes local air pollution plastic pollution and contributes to greenhouse gas emissions and climate change.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars and vans caused 10% of energy-related carbon dioxide emissions in 2022.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] As of 2023, electric cars produce about half the emissions over their lifetime as diesel and petrol cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] This is set to improve as countries produce more of their electricity from low-carbon sources.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars consume almost a quarter of world oil production as of 2019.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cities planned around cars are often less dense, which leads to further emissions, as they are less walkable, for instance.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] A growing demand for large SUVs is driving up emissions from cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Cars are a major cause of air pollution, which stems from exhaust gas in diesel and petrol cars and from dust from brakes, tyres, and road wear.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Heavy metals and microplastics (from tyres) are also released into the environment, during production, use, and at the end of life.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Mining related to car manufacturing and oil spills both cause water pollution.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Animals and plants are often negatively affected by cars through habitat destruction and fragmentation caused by the road network, as well as pollution.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Animals are also killed every year on roads by cars, referred to as roadkill.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] More recent road developments are including significant environmental mitigation in their designs, such as green bridges (designed to allow wildlife crossings) and creating wildlife corridors.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Governments use fiscal policies, such as road tax, to discourage the purchase and use of more polluting cars; Vehicle emission standards ban the sale of new highly pollution cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Many countries plan to stop selling fossil cars altogether between 2025 and 2050.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Various cities have implemented low-emission zones, banning old fossil fuel and Amsterdam is planning to ban fossil fuel cars completely.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Some cities make it easier for people to choose other forms of transport, such as cycling.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Many Chinese cities limit licensing of fossil fuel cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Mass production of personal motor vehicles in the United States and other developed countries with extensive territories, such as Australia, Argentina, and France, vastly increased individual and group mobility and greatly expanded economic development in urban, suburban, exurban, and rural areas.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Growth in the popularity of cars and commuting has led to traffic congestion.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Moscow, Istanbul, Bogotá, Mexico City and São Paulo were the world's most congested cities in 2018 according to INRIX, a data analytics company.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In the United States, the transport divide and car dependency resulting from domination of car-based transport systems presents barriers to employment in low-income neighbourhoods, with many low-income individuals and families forced to run cars they cannot afford in order to maintain their income.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Dependency on automobiles by African Americans may result in exposure to the hazards of driving while black and other types of racial discrimination related to buying, financing and insuring them.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Air pollution from cars increases the risk of a number of diseases, including stroke, heart disease, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), lung cancer, respiratory infections and aggravated asthma.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Air pollution is also linked to global impacts on all aspects of sexual reproduction from male and female fertility to fetal development, birth outcomes, and long-term health of offspring.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Children are extra vulnerable to air pollution, as their bodies are still developing and air pollution in children is linked to the development of asthma, childhood cancer, and neurocognitive issues such as autism.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The growth in popularity of the car allowed cities to sprawl, therefore encouraging more travel by car, resulting in inactivity and obesity, which in turn can lead to increased risk of a variety of diseases.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] When places are designed around cars, children have fewer opportunities to go places by themselves and lose opportunities to become more independent.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Intensive development of conventional battery electric vehicles is continuing into the 2020s, for example lithium iron phosphate batteries are safer and cheaper.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Other car technologies that are under development include wireless charging.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Software is increasing and may have many new uses, for example automatically not hitting pedestrians.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] New materials which may replace steel car bodies include aluminium, fibreglass, carbon fibre, biocomposites, and carbon nanotubes.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Telematics technology is allowing more and more people to share cars, on a pay-as-you-go basis, through car share and carpool schemes.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Communication is also evolving due to connected car systems.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Microwave weapons which can disable cars are being tested.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Fully self-driving vehicles, also known as autonomous cars, already exist as robotaxis in some locations.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Laws for the regulation of self-driving cars will need updating before widespread deployment can happen.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Car-share arrangements and carpooling are also increasingly popular, in the US and Europe.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Services like car sharing offer residents to "share" a vehicle rather than own a car in already congested neighbourhoods.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The automotive industry designs, develops, manufactures, markets, and sells the world's motor vehicles, more than three-quarters of which are cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In 2020, there were 56 million cars manufactured worldwide, down from 67 million the previous year.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The automotive industry in China produces by far the most (20 million in 2020), followed by Japan (seven million), then Germany, South Korea, and India.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The largest market is China, followed by the US.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] There are around 1.644 billion cars in use worldwide as of January 2025; they burn over a trillion litres (0.26×10^12 US gal; 0.22×10^12 imp gal) of petrol and diesel fuel yearly, consuming about 50 exajoules (14,000 TWh) of energy.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The number of cars is increasing rapidly in China and India.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In the opinion of some, urban transport systems based around the car have proved unsustainable, consuming excessive energy, affecting the health of populations, and delivering a declining level of service despite increasing investment.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Many of these negative effects fall disproportionately on those social groups who are also least likely to own and drive cars.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The sustainable transport movement focuses on solutions to these problems.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] The car industry is also facing increasing competition from the public transport sector, as some people re-evaluate their use of private vehicles.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] In July 2021, the European Commission introduced the "Fit for 55" legislation package, outlining crucial directives for the automotive sector's future.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] According to this package, by 2035, all newly sold cars in the European market must be Zero-emissions vehicles.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Established alternatives for some aspects of car use include public transport such as busses, trolleybusses, trains, subways, tramways, light rail, cycling, and walking.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Bicycle sharing systems have been established in China and many European cities, including Copenhagen and Amsterdam.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Similar programmes have been developed in large US cities.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Additional individual modes of transport, such as personal rapid transit could serve as an alternative to cars if they prove to be socially accepted.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] A study which checked the costs and the benefits of introducing Low Traffic Neighbourhood in London found the benefits overpass the costs approximately by 100 times in the first 20 years and the difference is growing over time.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] Motorsport is a sport involving high speed racing and drifting.
[src:emergency-light/automobile] It includes various racing series such as Formula One, IndyCar Series, NASCAR, World Rally Championship and MotoGP.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] An **emergency light** is a battery-backed lighting device that switches on automatically when a building experiences a power outage.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] In the United States, emergency lights are standard in new commercial and high occupancy residential buildings, such as college dormitories, apartments, and hotels.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Most building codes in the US require that they be installed in older buildings as well.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Incandescent light bulbs were originally used in emergency lights, before fluorescent lights and later light-emitting diodes (LEDs) superseded them in the 21st century.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] By the nature of the device, an emergency light is designed to come on when the power goes out.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Every model, therefore, requires some sort of a battery or generator system that could provide electricity to the lights during a blackout.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] The earliest models were incandescent light bulbs which could dimly light an area during a blackout and perhaps provide enough light to solve the power problem or evacuate the building.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] It was quickly realized, however, that a more focused, brighter, and longer-lasting light was needed.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Modern emergency floodlights provide a high-lumen, wide-coverage light that can illuminate an area quite well.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Some lights are halogen, and provide a light source and intensity similar to that of an automobile headlight.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Early battery backup systems were huge, dwarfing the size of the lights for which they provided power.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] The systems normally used lead acid batteries to store a full 120 VDC charge.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] For comparison, an automobile uses a single lead acid battery as part of the ignition system.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Simple transistor or relay technology was used to switch on the lights and battery supply in the event of a power failure.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] The size of these units, as well as the weight and cost, made them relatively rare installations.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] As technology developed further, the voltage requirements for lights dropped, and subsequently the size of the batteries was reduced as well.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Modern lights are only as large as the bulbs themselves - the battery fits quite well in the base of the fixture.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] In the United States, modern emergency lighting is installed in virtually every commercial and high occupancy residential building.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] The lights consist of one or more incandescent bulbs or one or more clusters of high-intensity light-emitting diodes (LED).
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] The emergency lighting heads have usually been either incandescent PAR 36 sealed beams or wedge base lamps, but LED illumination is increasingly common.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] All units have some sort of a device to focus and intensify the light they produce.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] This can either be in the form of a plastic cover over the fixture, or a reflector placed behind the light source.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Most individual light sources can be rotated and aimed for where light is needed most in an emergency, such as toward fire exits.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Modern fixtures usually have a test button of some sort which simulates a power failure and causes the unit to switch on the lights and operate from battery power, even if the main power is still on.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Modern systems are operated with relatively low voltage, usually from 6-12 VDC.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] This both reduces the size of the batteries required and reduces the load on the circuit to which the emergency light is wired.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Modern fixtures include a small transformer in the base of the fixture which steps-down the voltage from main current to the low voltage required by the lights.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Batteries are commonly made of lead-calcium, and can last for 10 years or more on continuous charge.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] US fire safety codes require a minimum of 90 minutes on battery power during a power outage along the path of egress.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] As there are strict requirements to provide an average of one foot candle of light along the path of egress, emergency lighting should be selected carefully to ensure codes are met.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] In recent years, emergency lighting has made less use of the traditional two-head unit - with manufacturers stretching the concept of emergency lighting to accommodate and integrate emergency lighting into the architecture.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Self-contained emergency lighting fittings may operate in "Maintained" mode (illuminated all the time or controlled by a switch) or "Non-Maintained" mode (illuminated only when the normal supply fails).
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Some emergency lighting manufacturers offer dimming solutions for common area emergency lighting to allow energy savings for building owners when unoccupied using embedded sensors.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Another popular method for lighting designers, architects and contractors are battery backup ballasts that install within or adjacent to existing lighting fixtures.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Upon sensing power loss, the ballasts switch into emergency mode turning the existing lighting into emergency lighting in order to meet both the NFPA's Life Safety Code and the National Electrical Code without the need of wiring separate circuits or external wall mounts.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Codes of practice for remote mounted emergency lighting generally mandate that wiring from the central power source to emergency luminaires be kept segregated from other wiring, and constructed in fire resistant cabling and wiring systems.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Codes of practice lay down minimum illumination levels in escape routes and open areas.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Codes of practice also lay down requirements governing siting of emergency lighting fittings, for example the UK code of practice, BS5266, specifies that a fitting must be within 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) horizontal distance of a fire alarm call point or location for fire fighting appliances.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] The most recent codes of practice require the designer to allow for both failure of the supply to the building and the failure of an individual lighting circuit.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] BS5266 requires that when Non Maintained fittings are used, they must be supplied from the same final circuit as the main lighting circuit in the area.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Emergency lights test, or emergency lighting compliance (ELC), is the process of ensuring that emergency lights are in working order and compliant with safety regulations.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] This typically involves monthly and annual tests, as well as regular maintenance and replacement of batteries and bulbs. emergency lights test is important to ensure that emergency lights will be able to provide adequate illumination in the event of a power outage or other emergency situation.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] According to British fire safety law, an entire assessment of the system must be conducted yearly and “flick-tested” at least once a month.
[src:emergency-light/emergency-light] Emergency lighting serves multiple purposes: illuminating pathways for occupants to escape from hazardous situations, as well as helping individuals discover nearby fire-fighting equipment in case of emergencies.
